### **Texas Compliance for Before/Afters**\
\
**Texas Medical Board Rules (22 TAC Ch. 164):**\
\
**
\f1 \uc0\u9989 
\f0  YOU CAN:**\
- Post before/after photos with written patient consent\
- Show results of treatments you actually performed\
- Use photos in advertising and social media\
\
**
\f1 \uc0\u10060 
\f0  YOU CANNOT:**\
- Make guarantees or promises of specific results\
- Use stock photos or photos of patients you didn't treat\
- Make false or misleading claims\
- Imply results are typical when they're exceptional\
\
**REQUIRED:**\
- Written consent from every patient (HIPAA-compliant form)\
- Disclaimers: "Results may vary," "Individual results not guaranteed"\
- Truthful representation (same lighting, angle, no heavy editing)\
- Disclose if photos are enhanced or edited\
\
**Best Practices:**\
- Get consent at time of treatment (while they're happy with results)\
- Use standardized photography setup (same lighting, background, camera settings)\
- Show realistic timelines (don't claim overnight results)\
- Emphasize your "natural" positioning through subtle before/afters (not dramatic)\
