## **11. TEXAS COMPLIANCE & REGULATORY UPDATES (2025)**\
\
### **Texas Medical Board Rules (Updated 2025)**\
\
**Critical Compliance Requirements:**\
\
**1. Physician Supervision & Display (22 TAC \'a7169.28)**\
\
**Required:**\
- Display supervising/delegating physician name and Texas medical license number in:\
  - Each treatment room\
  - Public areas (waiting room, reception)\
- Staff name badges must show credentials (RN, LVN, etc.)\
\
**Implementation:**\
- Create professional signage (Canva template, print at FedEx)\
- Include: "Supervised by Dr. [Name], Texas Medical License #[Number]"\
- Place in every treatment room and waiting area\
- Ensure all staff wear name badges with credentials\
\
**Penalty for Non-Compliance**: TMB enforcement action, fines, potential license issues\
\
**2. Advertising & Marketing (22 TAC Ch. 164)**\
\
**Required:**\
- Advertising must not be false, misleading, or deceptive\
- Must maintain records of all advertising for 4 years\
- Cannot guarantee or promise specific results\
- Must include required disclosures\
\
**Prohibited:**\
- Guaranteeing results ("You WILL look 10 years younger")\
- Using patient photos without written consent\
- Implying results are typical when they're exceptional\
- Misrepresenting credentials or training\
- Using stock photos and claiming they're your results\
\
**Best Practices:**\
- Always include disclaimer: "Results may vary; individual results not guaranteed"\
- Get written consent for all before/after photos (HIPAA-compliant form)\
- Use truthful, accurate representations (same lighting, angle, no heavy editing)\
- Disclose if photos are enhanced or edited\
- Keep copies of all ads, social posts, emails for 4 years\
\
**3. Before/After Photos (Specific Requirements)**\
\
**Required:**\
- Written patient consent (HIPAA-compliant authorization form)\
- Truthful representation (same lighting, angle, expression)\
- Disclaimer: "Results may vary"\
- Disclose if edited or enhanced\
\
**Prohibited:**\
- Using photos without consent\
- Using stock photos or photos of patients you didn't treat\
- Heavily editing to misrepresent results\
- Implying guaranteed outcomes\
\
**Implementation:**\
- Create consent form (template: "I authorize Summer House Aesthetics to use my before/after photos for marketing purposes...")\
- Get signed at time of treatment (when they're happy with results)\
- Store securely (HIPAA compliance)\
- Include disclaimer on every before/after post/image\
\
**4. GLP-1 & Compounded Medications (FDA Enforcement)**\
\
**Current Climate** (2025):\
- FDA increasing enforcement on compounded semaglutide claims\
- Cannot use brand names (Ozempic, Wegovy) if you're using compounded versions\
- Must disclose if medication is compounded (not FDA-approved branded version)\
- Cannot make weight loss guarantees\
\
**Required Messaging:**\
- "We offer compounded semaglutide (not branded Ozempic/Wegovy)"\
- "Results vary; weight loss not guaranteed"\
- "Physician-supervised protocol"\
- Avoid: "Lose 20 lbs in 3 months guaranteed"\
\
**Best Practices:**\
- Be transparent about compounded vs. branded\
- Emphasize medical supervision and safety\
- Focus on "body composition optimization" not "weight loss miracle"\
- Monitor FDA enforcement actions (landscape is changing)\
\
**5. Telehealth & Prescribing (Texas Rules)**\
\
**If offering GLP-1s or peptides via telehealth:**\
- Must establish physician-patient relationship (can be via telemedicine)\
- Physician must review medical history, conduct appropriate evaluation\
- Cannot prescribe controlled substances via telemedicine (GLP-1s are not controlled, but monitor)\
- Must maintain medical records\
\
**Best Practices:**\
- Initial consultation (in-person or video)\
- Medical history intake form\
- Physician review and approval\
- Ongoing monitoring (monthly check-ins)\
- Document everything\
\
**6. Scope of Practice (Nurse Injectors)**\
\
**What RNs CAN do in Texas (under physician delegation):**\
- Administer neurotoxin (Botox, Dysport)\
- Administer dermal fillers\
- Perform laser treatments (with training)\
- Administer GLP-1s and peptides (under physician protocol)\
\
**What RNs CANNOT do:**\
- Prescribe medications (must be physician)\
- Diagnose medical conditions independently\
- Perform procedures outside scope of delegation agreement\
\
**Required:**\
- Written delegation agreement with supervising physician\
- Physician oversight and availability\
- Training and competency documentation\
\
**7. Insurance & Liability**\
\
**Required Coverage:**\
- Professional liability insurance (malpractice)\
- General liability insurance (premises, slip-and-fall)\
- Product liability (if selling skincare products)\
\
**Recommended:**\
- Cyber liability (if storing patient data electronically)\
- Business interruption insurance\
\
**Best Practices:**\
- Review policies annually\
- Ensure coverage limits are adequate ($1M-$2M recommended)\
- Notify insurer of new services or equipment\
\
